{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"97286426-ea35-4c9d-9620-93fe3f69118a","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for **Apple crash reports** rather than .NET-style dumps:\n\n1. **Crash Reports** are saved automatically by macOS at:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for files named `<YourApp>_<date>.crash` or `.ips`.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and navigate to **Crash Reports** in the sidebar to browse them with a GUI.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited   # enable before running\n   ```\n   Cores land in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can inspect them with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb <your-app-binary> -c /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n\n4. For **real-time** crash info, run your app under `lldb` directly:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./MyApp\n   run\n   ```\n\nThe `.crash`/`.ips` files in `DiagnosticReports` are usually the quickest path — they include the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a7061e82-a2c8-4d83-ba52-3b5fb7ac3937","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":341,"requestId":"1BC0:1AA4EA:15EDF50:189CEC0:6A028692"},"id":"b9759a38-a2b4-4b8b-96c5-ade4f8b8bf68","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:47:08.772Z","parentId":"d30859da-982d-47da-89e7-2ad309f9ec9a"}
